O inverno vai chegar em abril, com a estreia da oitava e última temporada da série mais comentada de sempre. “Guerra dos Tronos” chega ao final após nove anos na televisão. summary: at exactly 50:42 in episode 6 of season 6 (blood of my blood), violins start playing during the targaryen theme... (listen HERE...
body:
at exactly 50:42 in episode 6 of season 6 (blood of my blood), violins start playing during the targaryen theme… (listen HERE to see what part I mean) and i get chills and tears in my eyes. every. single. time.  i cannot explain it and i hope i never find out why because i think that’s part of the beauty of it. i have no idea how ramin dajwadi came up with such a beautiful track… but i am so thankful.

 i love dany. i love her story of overcoming everything. i just love daenerys targaryen and everything good she represents

title: Game of Thrones Season 8: Speculations
body:
The clock is running and soon enough we are going to see the final ending of our favourite franchise. Until then, there still is lots of room for speculation.

The tv series turned out entirely different compared to GRRM’s books. This is why I do believe that the ending will be a kind of fan service and not that dramatic as it used to be in previous seasons.

Facts that we can already predict are that Cersei is NOT actually pregnant, Daenerys will find out about her actual past and meet Jorah again. Sam and Bran will be totally important and the masters of it all. Also, Jon and Dany will most likely get into a fight as soon as they find about about their relations (or not).

We still have so many unanswered questions that it is hard to imagine to have those all answered within 8 episodes. I have high hopes to get some justice and a bigger Theon plot (and less Euron, thx).

What do you think is going to happen in the final season? Do you have any wishes for further speculations and theories?

summary: 1) Jon's lack of respect for Sansa is coz he's a sexist. That infamous 'no need of blushing maidens looking to be protected'  &...
question: 1) Jon's lack of respect for Sansa is coz he's a sexist. That infamous 'no need of blushing maidens looking to be protected'  & ' not some willowy creature who sits in a tower' is because deep down he really wants a lady lyk that to fulfill his deepest dream of having a lady wife & children & ruling winterfell. He wants a lady wife but admires only warriors. He wants to fulfill the idea of being knight to a princess in a tower. So this stems from his bastard/mommy problems coz he's been made to
answer:
2) he’s inferior coz he’s a bastard so he can’t have them. Also the only mother figure in his lyf cat was a lady who hated him. But I also believe that it goes beyond his bastard issues. I think he’s sexist in general. U’ve instances lyk him calling myrcella insipid just coz she was blushing at Robb(later readers know that she’s quite intelligent), he says how joff uses Cersei’s sigil too when royal sigil is enough to which Arya tells him woman is important too, when gilly cries he says she

3) thinks tears can change his mind(implying he thinks woman use tears to change men’s mind), he calls ladies with queen selyse as pallid etc & in show u’ve ygritte saying she’s not lyk dumb girls he grew up with & he doesn’t deny. There could be more examples in the books. Point he’s sexist in general. Just lyk Sansa gets over classism, j will have to get over his sexism with Sansa. We’ll see that in s8 when S gets kidnapped & he’ll realise what a mean ungrateful ass he has been to her. & I’ll

4) be angry coz S would have been beaten/tortured by the mountain by then & ofc S will eventually forgive him, coz he doesn’t deserve that forgiveness. He not only looks down on her, scoffs on her opinion (‘that’s a good advice’ in tent scene) but also dismisses her suffering by trusting Cersei, saying he’s faced worse than ramsay. & then we’ve Arya & lyanna Mormont looking down on ladies. By the end of s8 he’ll start treating her as an equal.

I’ll be glad if he stops being sexist but do D&D think that’s a problem? From the way they write women, do you think they look at Jon and Sansa’s interactions and think ‘this needs to be changed’ or will they ignore the problem forcing us to pretend there’s character development?
